////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
3. LCA
////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Children compute their best path UP to current node (bottom-up)
Current node JOINS left and right to form the full path (the twist)
But can only send ONE side back UP to its parent

int helper(TreeNode root) {
    // 1. BASE CASE
    if (root == null) return 0;  // or MIN_VALUE depending on problem
    
    // 2. RECURSE into children FIRST
    int left  = helper(root.left);
    int right = helper(root.right);
    
    // 3. JOINING POINT — use BOTH sides (this node is the LCA)
    // Join? Combine values of node and children - all of them
    // This is for maintaining a global answer
    globalMax = Math.max(globalMax, left + right + root.val);
    
    // 4. RETURN only ONE side UP to parent
    // This return statement will still be present, as info has to flow from bottom to TOP
    // How will the parent get information? From return value from the children 
    return Math.max(left, right) + root.val;
}
```

---

## The 4 parts always appear in this order:
```
1. null check         → base case
2. recurse left       → get best path from left subtree
3. recurse right      → get best path from right subtree
4. JOIN at current    → combine left + root + right for globalMax
   RETURN one side UP → parent can only extend in ONE direction
```

---

## Why you can only return ONE side up:
```
        1
       / \
      2   3
     / \
    4   5

At node 2:
  left  = 4
  right = 5

Path 4→2→5 is valid HERE at node 2.
But if node 2 sends BOTH sides up to node 1:
  1 would try to make path: 4→2→1→3
  That means going DOWN to 4, back UP to 2, UP to 1, DOWN to 3
  A node (2) appears twice — INVALID!

So node 2 can only send its BEST single side up:
  max(4, 5) + 2 = 7   ← only one direction

Children send best SINGLE path UP
Parent JOINS both sides for globalMax
Parent sends best SINGLE side further UP
```

