## All three path types side by side:
```
Top-down          Bottom-up         Node-to-node (LCA)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
preorder          postorder         postorder + global tracker
info via params   info via return   info via return + joined at LCA
parent → child    child → parent    child → parent, joined at LCA
no global needed  no global needed  NEEDS global variable
void/bool         returns value     returns ONE side, tracks BOTH
```

The main difference between Bottom UP and LCA is that LCA needs global variable.
Why?
Depends, if the answer gets lost while propogatin from bottom to top - we need a global variable => LCA
if answer can be propogated correctly from bottom to top - without getting lost => Postorder bottom-up
Postorder — each node receives results from children and combines them to produce its own result, 
which gets passed up unchanged in meaning

                              Postorder                                   LCA
Question each node asks   "What is the result for my subtree?"  "What did you find below you?"
Meaning of return value       Same throughout the tree              Changes depending on the node position
How children results combine  Symmetric (and, +, max)      Asymmetric — depends on what both children return
Answer location               Answer can be anywhere in the tree    Answer can be anywhere in the tree
