4. Iterative Descent or Pointer Chasing for BST 
/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

No stack, no queue — just a single pointer that moves down the tree one step at a time following a rule.

General tree traversal needs a stack. That is because in a general tree you need to remember which nodes 
to come back to — you go left, then need to backtrack and go right.
But this problem is a BST with a very specific property. At every node you know with 100% certainty which
direction to go. You never need to backtrack. You never need to remember anything.

Because you never backtrack, you need zero memory of previous nodes. The pointer just falls down the tree 
like a marble rolling downhill.

A stack is needed when the path forward is ambiguous — you might need to explore multiple directions. 
Pointer chasing works when the path forward is deterministic — exactly one correct direction at every step.


